					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Coo=
rdinates comprising a distance and two angles</div>
<p class=3D"mw-empty-elt">
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:3D_Spherical.svg" class=3D"mw-file-descriptio=
n"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4f/3D=
_Spherical.svg/250px-3D_Spherical.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250"=
 height=3D"217" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"600" data-file=
-height=3D"520"></a><figcaption>The <i><b>physics convention</b></i>. Spher=
ical coordinates (<b><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">r</span></b>, <b><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">=CE=B8</span></b>, <b><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:=
italic;">=CF=86</span></b>) as commonly used: (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/International_Organization_for_Standardization" title=3D"Inter=
national Organization for Standardization">ISO</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/ISO/IEC_80000" title=3D"ISO/IEC 80000">80000-2:2019</a>): =
radial distance <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">r=
</span> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slant_distance" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Slant distance">slant distance</a> to origin), polar =
angle <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=B8</spa=
n> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theta" title=3D"Theta">theta</=
a>) (angle with respect to positive polar axis), and azimuthal angle <span =
class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=86</span> (<a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phi" title=3D"Phi">phi</a>) (angle of rot=
ation from the initial meridian plane). <i><b>This is the convention follow=
ed in this article.</b></i></figcaption></figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathem=
atics">mathematics</a>, a <b>spherical coordinate system</b> specifies a gi=
ven point in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three-dimensional_spa=
ce" title=3D"Three-dimensional space">three-dimensional space</a> by using =
a distance and two angles as its three <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Coordinate_system" title=3D"Coordinate system">coordinates</a>. These =
are
</p>
<ul><li>the <b>radial distance</b> <b><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D=
"font-style:italic;">r</span></b> along the line connecting the point to a =
fixed point called the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Origin_(mat=
hematics)" title=3D"Origin (mathematics)">origin</a>;</li>
<li>the <b>polar angle</b> <b><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-st=
yle:italic;">=CE=B8</span></b> between this radial line and a given <i>pola=
r axis</i>;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spherical_coordinate_system#cite_note-1"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>a<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and=
</li>
<li>the <b>azimuthal angle</b> <b><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fon=
t-style:italic;">=CF=86</span></b>, which is the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Angle_of_rotation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Angle of r=
otation">angle of rotation</a> of the radial line around the polar axis.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Spherical_coordinate_system#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>b<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<p>(See graphic regarding the "physics convention".)=20
</p><p>Once the radius is fixed, the three coordinates (<i>r</i>, <i>=CE=B8=
</i>, <i>=CF=86</i>), known as a 3-<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Tuple" title=3D"Tuple">tuple</a>, provide a coordinate system on a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sphere" title=3D"Sphere">sphere</a>, typi=
cally called the <b>spherical polar coordinates</b>.
The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plane_(geometry)" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Plane (geometry)">plane</a> passing through the origin a=
nd <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perpendicular" title=3D"Perpend=
icular">perpendicular</a> to the polar axis (where the polar angle is a <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Right_angle" title=3D"Right angle">ri=
ght angle</a>) is called the <i><b>reference plane</b></i> (sometimes <i><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundamental_plane_(spherical_coordin=
ates)" title=3D"Fundamental plane (spherical coordinates)">fundamental plan=
e</a></i>).
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Terminology">Terminology</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSpherical_coor=
dinate_system&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Ter=
minology"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</sp=
an></span></div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">The physics =
convention is followed in this article; (See both graphics re "physics conv=
ention" and re "mathematics convention".)</div>
<p>The radial distance from the fixed point of origin is also called the <i=
>radius</i>, or <i>radial line</i>, or <i>radial coordinate</i>. The polar =
angle may be called <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inclination=
_angle" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Inclination angle">inclination angle=
</a></i>, <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zenith_angle" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Zenith angle">zenith angle</a></i>, <i><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_vector" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Normal vector">normal angle</a></i>, or the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Colatitude" title=3D"Colatitude">colatitude</a></i>. The u=
ser may choose to replace the inclination angle by its <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angular_complement" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ang=
ular complement">complement</a>, the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Elevation_angle" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Elevation angle">elev=
ation angle</a></i> (or <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Altitud=
e_angle" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Altitude angle">altitude angle</a><=
/i>), measured upward between the reference plane and the radial line=E2=80=
=94i.e., from the reference plane upward (towards to the positive z-axis) t=
o the radial line. The <i>depression angle</i> is the negative of the eleva=
tion angle. <i>(See graphic re the "physics convention"=E2=80=94not "mathem=
atics convention".)</i>
</p><p>Both the use of symbols and the naming order of tuple coordinates di=
ffer among the several sources and disciplines. This article will use the I=
SO convention<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spherical_coordinate_system#cite_note-3"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
frequently encountered in <i>physics</i>, where the naming tuple gives the =
order as: radial distance, polar angle, azimuthal angle, or <i><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathm=
l-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http=
://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle (r,\theta ,\varph=
i )}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>r</mi>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mi>=CE=B8<!-- =CE=B8 --></mi>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mi>=CF=86<!-- =CF=86 --></mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle (r,\theta ,\v=
arphi )}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/d0fbf2e667b8c94c169165fc44e0d73e66c901a9" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:7.536ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle (r,=
\theta ,\varphi )}"></span></i>. (See graphic re the "physics convention".)=
 In contrast, the conventions in many mathematics books and texts give the =
naming order differently as: radial distance, "azimuthal angle", "polar ang=
le", and <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span cla=
ss=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"=
><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaysty=
le (\rho ,\theta ,\varphi )}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>=CF=81<!-- =CF=81 --></mi>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mi>=CE=B8<!-- =CE=B8 --></mi>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mi>=CF=86<!-- =CF=86 --></mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle (\rho ,\theta=
 ,\varphi )}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/0ea69ccecb586b659206091cb824b2bbf51b5498" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:7.69ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle (\rh=
o ,\theta ,\varphi )}"></span> or <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-=
element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y"=
 style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML=
" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle (r,\theta ,\varphi )}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
