        <mi>r</mi>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mi>=CE=B8<!-- =CE=B8 --></mi>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mi>=CF=86<!-- =CF=86 --></mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle (r,\theta ,\v=
arphi )}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/d0fbf2e667b8c94c169165fc44e0d73e66c901a9" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:7.536ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle (r,=
\theta ,\varphi )}"></span>=E2=80=94which switches the uses and meanings of=
 symbols =CE=B8 and =CF=86. Other conventions may also be used, such as <i>=
r</i> for a radius from the <i>z-</i>axis that is not from the point of ori=
gin. Particular care must be taken to check the meaning of the symbols.=20
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:3D_Spherical_2.svg" class=3D"mw-file-descript=
ion"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dc/=
3D_Spherical_2.svg/250px-3D_Spherical_2.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=
=3D"250" height=3D"231" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"558" d=
ata-file-height=3D"516"></a><figcaption>The <i><b>mathematics convention</b=
></i>. Spherical coordinates <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>r</i>, <i>=CE=B8</=
i>, <i>=CF=86</i>)</span> as typically used: radial distance <span class=3D=
"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">r</span>, azimuthal angle <span=
 class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=B8</span>, and pol=
ar angle <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=86</=
span>. + <i>The meanings of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-styl=
e:italic;">=CE=B8</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-sty=
le:italic;">=CF=86</span> have been swapped</i>=E2=80=94compared to the <b>=
physics convention</b>. The 'south'-direction x-axis is depicted but the 'n=
orth'-direction x-axis is not. (As in physics, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar"=
 style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=81</span> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Rho" title=3D"Rho">rho</a>) is often used instead of <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">r</span> to avoid confusion =
with the value <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">r<=
/span> in cylindrical and 2D polar coordinates.)</figcaption></figure>
<p>According to the conventions of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Geographical_coordinate_system" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Geographica=
l coordinate system">geographical coordinate systems</a>, positions are mea=
sured by latitude, longitude, and height (altitude). There are a number of =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Celestial_coordinate_system" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Celestial coordinate system">celestial coordinate=
 systems</a> based on different <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fu=
ndamental_plane_(spherical_coordinates)" title=3D"Fundamental plane (spheri=
cal coordinates)">fundamental planes</a> and with different terms for the v=
arious coordinates. The spherical coordinate systems used in mathematics no=
rmally use <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian" title=3D"Radian=
">radians</a> rather than <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Degree_(=
angle)" title=3D"Degree (angle)">degrees</a>; (note 90 degrees equals <span=
 class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">=CF=80</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"de=
n">2</span></span> radians). And these systems of the  <i>mathematics conve=
ntion</i> may measure the azimuthal angle <i>counterclockwise</i> (i.e., fr=
om the south direction <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ita=
lic;">x</span>-axis, or 180=C2=B0, towards the east direction <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">y</span>-axis, or +90=C2=B0)=
=E2=80=94rather than measure <i>clockwise</i> (i.e., from the north directi=
on x-axis, or 0=C2=B0, towards the east direction y-axis, or +90=C2=B0), as=
 done in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horizontal_coordinate=
_system" title=3D"Horizontal coordinate system">horizontal coordinate syste=
m</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Spherical_coordinate_system#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <i>(See =
graphic re "mathematics convention".)</i>
</p><p>The spherical coordinate system of the <i>physics convention</i> can=
 be seen as a generalization of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Polar_coordinate_system" title=3D"Polar coordinate system">polar coordina=
te system</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three-dimensional=
_space" title=3D"Three-dimensional space">three-dimensional space</a>.=20
It can be further extended to higher-dimensional spaces, and is then referr=
ed to as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/N-sphere#Spherical_coor=
dinates" title=3D"N-sphere"><i>hyperspherical coordinate system</i></a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Definition">Definition</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSpherical_coordi=
nate_system&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Defin=
ition"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span>=
</span></div>
<p>To define a spherical coordinate system, one must designate an <i>origin=
</i> point in space, <i><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:it=
alic;">O</span></i>, and two orthogonal directions: the <i>zenith reference=
</i> direction and the <i>azimuth reference</i> direction. These choices de=
termine a reference plane that is typically defined as containing the point=
 of origin and the <i>x=E2=80=93 and y=E2=80=93axes</i>, either of which ma=
y be designated as the <i>azimuth reference</i> direction. The reference pl=
ane is perpendicular (orthogonal) to the zenith direction, and typically is=
 designated "horizontal" to the zenith direction's "vertical". The spherica=
l coordinates of a point <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">P</span> then are defined as follows:
</p>
<ul><li>The <i>radius</i> or <i>radial distance</i> is the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_distance" title=3D"Euclidean distance">E=
uclidean distance</a> from the origin <i><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">O</span></i> to <i><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" sty=
le=3D"font-style:italic;">P</span></i>.</li>
<li>The <i>inclination</i> (or <i>polar angle</i>) is the signed angle from=
 the zenith reference direction to the line segment <span class=3D"texhtml =
mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">OP</span>. (<i>Elevation</i> may be used=
 as the polar angle instead of <i>inclination</i>; see below.)</li>
<li>The <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Azimuth" title=3D"Azimu=
th">azimuth</a></i> (or <i>azimuthal angle</i>) is the signed angle measure=
d from the <i>azimuth reference</i> direction to the orthogonal projection =
of the radial line segment <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style=
:italic;">OP</span> on the reference plane.</li></ul>
<p>The sign of the azimuth is determined by designating the rotation that i=
s the <i>positive</i> sense of turning about the zenith. This choice is arb=
itrary, and is part of the coordinate system definition.=20
(If the inclination is either zero or 180 degrees (=3D <span class=3D"texht=
ml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=80</span> radians), the azimuth i=
s arbitrary. If the radius is zero, both azimuth and inclination are arbitr=
ary.)
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horizontal_coordinate_s=
ystem" title=3D"Horizontal coordinate system"><i>elevation</i></a> is the s=
igned angle from the x-y reference plane to the radial line segment <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">OP</span>, where positiv=
e angles are designated as upward, towards the zenith reference. <i>Elevati=
on</i> is 90 degrees (=3D <span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tio=
n"><span class=3D"num"><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ita=
lic;">=CF=80</span></span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"de=
n">2</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span> radians) <i>minus inclination</i>. Thus,=
 if the inclination is 60 degrees (=3D <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-=
style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=
=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num"><span class=3D"texhtml mv=
ar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=80</span></span><span class=3D"sr-only=
">/</span><span class=3D"den">3</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span> radians), the=
n the elevation is 30 degrees (=3D <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-styl=
e" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=
=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num"><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=80</span></span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</s=
pan><span class=3D"den">6</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span> radians).
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra" title=3D=
"Linear algebra">linear algebra</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Euclidean_vector" title=3D"Euclidean vector">vector</a> from the ori=
gin <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">O</span> to t=
he point <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">P</span>=
 is often called the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Position_v=
ector" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Position vector">position vector</a><=
/i> of <i>P</i>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Conventions">Conventions</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSpherical_coor=
dinate_system&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Con=
ventions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</sp=
an></span></div>
<p>Several different conventions exist for representing spherical coordinat=
es and prescribing the naming order of their symbols. The 3-tuple number se=
t <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"m=
we-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math =
xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle (r,\=
theta ,\varphi )}">
