        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>r</mi>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mi>=CE=B8<!-- =CE=B8 --></mi>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mi>=CF=86<!-- =CF=86 --></mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle (r,\theta ,\v=
arphi )}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/d0fbf2e667b8c94c169165fc44e0d73e66c901a9" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:7.536ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle (r,=
\theta ,\varphi )}"></span> denotes radial distance, the polar angle=E2=80=
=94"inclination", or as the alternative, "elevation"=E2=80=94and the azimut=
hal angle. It is the common practice within the physics convention, as spec=
ified by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Organizatio=
n_for_Standardization" title=3D"International Organization for Standardizat=
ion">ISO</a> standard <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_80000-2"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"ISO 80000-2">80000-2:2019</a>, and earlier =
in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_31-11" title=3D"ISO 31-11">=
ISO 31-11</a> (1992).=20
</p><p><i>As stated above, this article describes the ISO "physics conventi=
on"=E2=80=94unless otherwise noted.</i>
</p><p>However, some authors (including mathematicians) use the symbol <i>=
=CF=81</i> (rho) for radius, or radial distance, <i>=CF=86</i> for inclinat=
ion (or elevation) and <i>=CE=B8</i> for azimuth=E2=80=94while others keep =
the use of <i>r</i> for the radius; all which "provides a logical extension=
 of the usual polar coordinates notation".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-http://mathwo=
rld.wolfram.com/SphericalCoordinates.html_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spherical_coordinate_system#cite_note-htt=
p://mathworld.wolfram.com/SphericalCoordinates.html-5"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> As to ord=
er, some authors list the azimuth <i>before</i> the inclination (or the ele=
vation) angle. Some combinations of these choices result in a <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Right-hand_rule" title=3D"Right-hand rule">left=
-handed</a> coordinate system. The standard "physics convention" 3-tuple se=
t <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"m=
we-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math =
xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle (r,\=
theta ,\varphi )}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>r</mi>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mi>=CE=B8<!-- =CE=B8 --></mi>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mi>=CF=86<!-- =CF=86 --></mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle (r,\theta ,\v=
arphi )}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
