tle=3D"Cylindrical coordinate system">cylindrical coordinates</a>, where <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=B8</span> is of=
ten used for the azimuth.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-http://mathworld.wolfram.com/S=
phericalCoordinates.html_5-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Spherical_coordinate_system#cite_note-http://mathworld.wolf=
ram.com/SphericalCoordinates.html-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Angles are typically measured in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Degree_(angle)" title=3D"Degree (angle)">degrees</a> (=C2=B0) or in <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian" title=3D"Radian">radians</a=
> (rad), where 360=C2=B0&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;2<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=80</span> rad. The use of degrees is most commo=
n in geography, astronomy, and engineering, where radians are commonly used=
 in mathematics and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theoretical_ph=
ysics" title=3D"Theoretical physics">theoretical physics</a>. The unit for =
radial distance is usually determined by the context, as occurs in applicat=
ions of the 'unit sphere', see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sph=
erical_coordinate_system#Applications">applications</a>.
</p><p>When the system is used to designate physical three-space, it is cus=
tomary to assign positive to azimuth angles measured in the <i>counterclock=
wise</i> sense from the reference direction on the reference plane=E2=80=94=
as seen from the "zenith" side of the plane. This convention is used in par=
ticular for geographical coordinates, where the "zenith" direction is <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/North" title=3D"North">north</a> and th=
e positive azimuth (longitude) angles are measured eastwards from some <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_meridian" title=3D"Prime meridia=
n">prime meridian</a>.
</p>
