ach point, the user must restrict the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Interval_(mathematics)" title=3D"Interval (mathematics)">range, aka int=
erval</a>, of each coordinate. A common choice is:
</p>
<div class=3D"plainlist" style=3D"margin-left: 1.6em;">
<ul><li>radial distance: <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i> =E2=89=A5 0,</spa=
n></li>
<li>polar angle: <span class=3D"texhtml">0=C2=B0 =E2=89=A4 <i>=CE=B8</i> =
=E2=89=A4 180=C2=B0</span>, or <span class=3D"texhtml">0 rad =E2=89=A4 <i>=
=CE=B8</i> =E2=89=A4 <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">=CF=80</span> rad</span>,</li>
<li>azimuth&nbsp;: <span class=3D"texhtml">0=C2=B0 =E2=89=A4  <i>=CF=86</i>=
 &lt; 360=C2=B0</span>, or <span class=3D"texhtml">0 rad =E2=89=A4  <i>=CF=
=86</i> &lt; 2<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=
=80</span> rad</span>.</li></ul>
</div>
<p>But instead of the interval <span class=3D"texhtml">[0=C2=B0, 360=C2=B0)=
</span>, the azimuth <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">=CF=86</span> is typically restricted to the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Interval_(mathematics)#Definitions" title=3D"Interval (mathe=
matics)">half-open interval</a> <span class=3D"texhtml">(=E2=88=92180=C2=B0=
, +180=C2=B0]</span>, or <span class=3D"texhtml">(=E2=88=92<span class=3D"t=
exhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=80</span>, +<span class=3D"te=
xhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=80</span> ]</span> radians, wh=
ich is the standard convention for geographic longitude.
</p><p>For the polar angle <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style=
:italic;">=CE=B8</span>, the range (interval) for inclination is <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml">[0=C2=B0, 180=C2=B0]</span>, which is equivalent to elevation=
 range (interval) <span class=3D"texhtml">[=E2=88=9290=C2=B0, +90=C2=B0]</s=
pan>. In geography, the latitude is the elevation.
</p><p>Even with these restrictions, if the polar angle (inclination) is 0=
=C2=B0 or 180=C2=B0=E2=80=94elevation is  =E2=88=9290=C2=B0 or +90=C2=B0=E2=
=80=94then the azimuth angle is arbitrary; and if <span class=3D"texhtml mv=
ar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">r</span> is zero, both azimuth and polar a=
ngles are arbitrary. To define the coordinates as unique, the user can asse=
rt the convention that (in these cases) the arbitrary coordinates are set t=
o zero.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Plotting">Plotting</h3><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSpherical_coordinate=
_system&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Plotting"=
><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span=
></div>
<p>To plot any dot from its spherical coordinates <span class=3D"texhtml">(=
<i>r</i>, <i>=CE=B8</i>, <i>=CF=86</i>)</span>, where <span class=3D"texhtm=
l mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=B8</span> is inclination, the user=
 would: move <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">r</s=
pan> units from the origin in the zenith reference direction (z-axis); then=
 rotate by the amount of the azimuth angle (<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=86</span>) about the origin  <i>from</i> the=
 designated <i>azimuth reference</i> direction, (i.e., either the x- or y-a=
xis, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spherical_coordinate_syst=
em#Definition">Definition</a>, above); and then rotate <i>from</i> the z-ax=
is by the amount of the <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:it=
alic;">=CE=B8</span> angle.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Applications">Applications<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSpherical_co=
ordinate_system&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: A=
pplications"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]<=
/span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Spherical_coordinate_system.s=
vg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/=
wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/Spherical_coordinate_system.svg/330px-Spherica=
l_coordinate_system.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"300" height=3D"300=
" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"690" data-file-height=3D"690=
"></a><figcaption>In the <i><b>mathematics convention</b></i>: A globe show=
ing a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_sphere" title=3D"Unit s=
phere">unit sphere</a>, with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tuple=
" title=3D"Tuple">tuple</a> coordinates of point <span class=3D"texhtml mva=
r" style=3D"font-style:italic;">P</span> (red): its radial distance <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">r</span> (red, not label=
ed);  its azimuthal angle <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:=
italic;">=CE=B8</span> (not labeled);  and its polar angle of <i>inclinatio=
n</i> <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=86</spa=
n> (not labeled).  The radial distance upward along the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zenith" title=3D"Zenith">zenith=E2=80=93axis</a> from=
 the point of origin to the surface of the sphere is assigned the value uni=
ty, or 1. + In this image, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style=
:italic;">r</span> appears to equal 4/6, or .67, (of unity); i.e., four of =
the six 'nested shells' to the surface. The azimuth angle <span class=3D"te=
xhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=B8</span> appears to equal pos=
itive 90=C2=B0, as rotated <i>counterclockwise</i> from the azimuth-referen=
ce x=E2=80=93axis;  and the inclination <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=86</span> appears to equal 30=C2=B0, as rotated=
 from the zenith=E2=80=93axis. (Note the 'full' rotation, or inclination, f=
rom the zenith=E2=80=93axis to the y=E2=80=93axis is 90=C2=B0).</figcaption=
></figure>
<p>Just as the two-dimensional <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Car=
tesian_coordinate_system" title=3D"Cartesian coordinate system">Cartesian c=
oordinate system</a> is useful=E2=80=94has a wide set of applications=E2=80=
=94on a planar surface, a two-dimensional spherical coordinate system is us=
eful on the surface of a sphere. For example, one sphere that is described =
in <i>Cartesian coordinates</i>  with the equation <span class=3D"texhtml">=
<i>x</i><sup>2</sup> + <i>y</i><sup>2</sup> + <i>z</i><sup>2</sup> =3D <i>c=
</i><sup>2</sup></span> can be described in <i>spherical coordinates</i> by=
 the simple equation <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i> =3D <i>c</i></span>. =
(In this system=E2=80=94<i>shown here in the mathematics convention</i>=E2=
=80=94the sphere is adapted as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/U=
nit_sphere" title=3D"Unit sphere">unit sphere</a>, where the radius is set =
to unity and then can generally be ignored, see graphic.)
</p><p>This (unit sphere) simplification is also useful when dealing with o=
bjects such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotation_matrix" ti=
tle=3D"Rotation matrix">rotational matrices</a>. Spherical coordinates are =
also useful in analyzing systems that have some degree of symmetry about a =
point, including: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiple_integra=
l" title=3D"Multiple integral">volume integrals</a> inside a sphere; the po=
tential energy field surrounding a concentrated mass or charge; or global w=
eather simulation in a planet's atmosphere.
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Bosch_36W_column_loudspeaker_polar_pattern.pn=
g" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/w=
ikipedia/commons/thumb/7/72/Bosch_36W_column_loudspeaker_polar_pattern.png/=
330px-Bosch_36W_column_loudspeaker_polar_pattern.png" decoding=3D"async" wi=
dth=3D"300" height=3D"398" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"606=
" data-file-height=3D"803"></a><figcaption>The output pattern of the indust=
rial <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Loudspeaker" title=3D"Loudspe=
aker">loudspeaker</a> shown here uses spherical polar plots taken at six fr=
equencies</figcaption></figure>
<p>Three dimensional modeling of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L=
oudspeaker" title=3D"Loudspeaker">loudspeaker</a> output patterns can be us=
ed to predict their performance. A number of polar plots are required, take=
n at a wide selection of frequencies, as the pattern changes greatly with f=
requency. Polar plots help to show that many loudspeakers tend toward omnid=
irectionality at lower frequencies.
</p><p>An important application of spherical coordinates provides for the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Separation_of_variables" title=3D"S=
eparation of variables">separation of variables</a> in two <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partial_differential_equations" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Partial differential equations">partial differential equations=
</a>=E2=80=94the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplace_equation"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Laplace equation">Laplace</a> and the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helmholtz_equation" title=3D"Helmholtz =
equation">Helmholtz equations</a>=E2=80=94that arise in many physical probl=
ems. The angular portions of the solutions to such equations take the form =
of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spherical_harmonics" title=3D"S=
pherical harmonics">spherical harmonics</a>. Another application is <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ergonomic_design" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Ergonomic design">ergonomic design</a>, where <span class=3D"texhtm=
l mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">r</span> is the arm length of a statio=
nary person and the angles describe the direction of the arm as it reaches =
out. The spherical coordinate system is also commonly used in 3D <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_development" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Game development">game development</a> to rotate the camera around the=
 player's position<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spherical_coordinate_system#cite_note-6"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"In_geography">In geography<=
/h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSpherical_co=
ordinate_system&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: I=
n geography"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]<=
/span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geographic_coordinat=
e_system" title=3D"Geographic coordinate system">Geographic coordinate syst=
em</a></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ECEF" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"ECEF">ECEF</a></div>
<p>Instead of inclination, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geo=
graphic_coordinate_system" title=3D"Geographic coordinate system">geographi=
c coordinate system</a> uses elevation angle (or <i><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Latitude" title=3D"Latitude">latitude</a></i>), in the ra=
nge (aka <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interval_(mathematics)" t=
itle=3D"Interval (mathematics)">domain</a>) <span class=3D"texhtml">=E2=88=
=9290=C2=B0 =E2=89=A4 <i>=CF=86</i> =E2=89=A4 90=C2=B0</span> and rotated n=
orth from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equator" title=3D"Eq=
uator">equator</a> plane. Latitude (i.e., <i>the angle</i> of latitude) may=
 be either <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geocentric_latitude"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Geocentric latitude">geocentric latitude</a=
></i>, measured (rotated) from the Earth's center=E2=80=94and designated va=
riously by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=88</i>, <i>q</i>, <i>=CF=86</i>=
=E2=80=B2, <i>=CF=86</i><sub>c</sub>, <i>=CF=86</i><sub>g</sub></span>=E2=
=80=94or <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geodetic_latitude" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Geodetic latitude">geodetic latitude</a></i>, m=
easured (rotated) from the observer's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Local_vertical" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Local vertical">local ve=
rtical</a>, and typically designated <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"=
font-style:italic;">=CF=86</span>.
The polar angle (inclination), which is 90=C2=B0 minus the latitude and ran=
ges from 0 to 180=C2=B0, is called <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Colatitude" title=3D"Colatitude">colatitude</a></i> in geography.
</p><p>The azimuth angle (or <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lo=
ngitude" title=3D"Longitude">longitude</a></i>) of a given position on Eart=
h, commonly denoted by <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ita=
lic;">=CE=BB</span>, is measured in degrees east or west from some conventi=
onal reference <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meridian_(geography=
)" title=3D"Meridian (geography)">meridian</a> (most commonly the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IERS_Reference_Meridian" title=3D"IERS Re=
ference Meridian">IERS Reference Meridian</a>); thus its domain (or range) =
is <span class=3D"texhtml">=E2=88=92180=C2=B0 =E2=89=A4 <i>=CE=BB</i> =E2=
=89=A4 180=C2=B0</span> and a given reading is typically designated "East" =
or "West". For positions on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ea=
rth" title=3D"Earth">Earth</a> or other solid <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Celestial_body" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Celestial body">=
celestial body</a>, the reference plane is usually taken to be the plane pe=
rpendicular to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axis_of_rotatio=
n" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Axis of rotation">axis of rotation</a>.=
=20
</p><p>Instead of the radial distance <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D=
"font-style:italic;">r</span> geographers commonly use <i><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Altitude" title=3D"Altitude">altitude</a></i> above=
 or below some local reference surface (<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Vertical_datum" title=3D"Vertical datum">vertical datum</a></i>), =
which, for example, may be the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mea=
n_sea_level" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mean sea level">mean sea level<=
/a>. When needed, the radial distance can be computed from the altitude by =
adding the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radius_of_Earth" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Radius of Earth">radius of Earth</a>, which is ap=
proximately 6,360&nbsp;=C2=B1&nbsp;11&nbsp;km (3,952&nbsp;=C2=B1&nbsp;7 mil=
es).
</p><p>However, modern geographical coordinate systems are quite complex, a=
nd the positions implied by these simple formulae may be inaccurate by seve=
ral kilometers. The precise standard meanings of <i>latitude, longitude</i>=
 and <i>altitude</i> are currently defined by the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/World_Geodetic_System" title=3D"World Geodetic System">Worl=
d Geodetic System</a> (WGS), and take into account the flattening of the Ea=
rth at the poles (about 21&nbsp;km or 13 miles) and many other details.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Planetary_coordinate_system=
" title=3D"Planetary coordinate system">Planetary coordinate systems</a> us=
e formulations analogous to the geographic coordinate system.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"In_astronomy">In astronomy<=
/h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSpherical_co=
ordinate_system&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: I=
n astronomy"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]<=
/span></span></div>
<p>A series of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astronomical_coordi=
nate_systems" title=3D"Astronomical coordinate systems">astronomical coordi=
nate systems</a> are used to measure the elevation angle from several <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundamental_plane_(spherical_coordinate=
s)" title=3D"Fundamental plane (spherical coordinates)">fundamental planes<=
/a>. These reference planes include:=20
the observer's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horizontal_coordina=
te_system" title=3D"Horizontal coordinate system">horizon</a>, the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galactic_coordinate_system" title=3D"Gala=
ctic coordinate system">galactic equator</a> (defined by the rotation of th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Milky_Way" title=3D"Milky Way">M=
ilky Way</a>), the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Celestial_equat=
or" title=3D"Celestial equator">celestial equator</a> (defined by <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earth%27s_rotation" title=3D"Earth's rota=
tion">Earth's rotation</a>), the plane of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Ecliptic_coordinate_system" title=3D"Ecliptic coordinate system=
">ecliptic</a> (defined by Earth's orbit around the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Sun" title=3D"Sun">Sun</a>), and the plane of the earth <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Terminator_(solar)" title=3D"Termin=
ator (solar)">terminator</a> (normal to the instantaneous direction to the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sun" title=3D"Sun">Sun</a>).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Coordinate_system_conversio=
ns">Coordinate system conversions</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/w/index.php?title=3DSpherical_coordinate_system&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sec=
tion=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Coordinate system conversions"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_common_coordinat=
e_transformations#To_spherical_coordinates" title=3D"List of common coordin=
ate transformations">List of common coordinate transformations =C2=A7&nbsp;=
To spherical coordinates</a></div>
<p>As the spherical coordinate system is only one of many three-dimensional=
 coordinate systems, there exist equations for converting coordinates betwe=
en the spherical coordinate system and others.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Cartesian_coordinates">Cart=
esian coordinates</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DSpherical_coordinate_system&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=
=3D"Edit section: Cartesian coordinates"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The spherical coordinates of a point in the ISO convention (i.e. for phy=
sics:  radius  <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">r<=
/span>, inclination  <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">=CE=B8</span>, azimuth  <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-styl=
e:italic;">=CF=86</span>) can be obtained from its <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Cartesian_coordinate_system" title=3D"Cartesian coordinate=
 system">Cartesian coordinates</a> <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>x</i>, <i>y<=
/i>, <i>z</i>)</span> by the formulae
